Being an introverted creative who is self-employed and placing great value on one's privacy should not be a contradiction, but sometimes it is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and behaving extroverted. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue tick from that service, be available around the clock, answer inquiries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it is a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and try to sell it to everyone. I am looking for new ways to run my business, while at the same time fighting against my long-held belief that you have to do something in a certain way in order to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I have canceled FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good about it.
Recently I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support and will move my business there in the next few weeks.
I have transferred my MX account to Proton and now have complete SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google anything for normal email validation.
3/3
